metadata.name: Kunza #236
metadata.description:
In 1949, the last known native speaker of Kunza died in the Atacama desert of Chile, leaving behind only fragments of a language that stretched back to when the Incans ruled the region. The textures, patterns, and colors in this project are not intended to be historically accurate: they tell a story. They are my attempt to reach into the past and imagine a vibrant history that is increasingly inaccessible.

Features include weave design, symbol layout, symbol style, and color palette.

After the image has fully rendered, pressing ‚Äòw‚Äô, ‚Äòr‚Äô, or ‚Äòc‚Äô will toggle different elements of the image, and pressing ‚Äòs‚Äô will download a PNG file.

metadata.name: The Climb #221
metadata.description:
The climb is about the search for purpose.

Everyone needs a purpose, a path that leads somewhere. Whether you reach it or not is not the point, it‚Äôs about the climb. The search for a purpose gives our life meaning. It gives us a reason to look for something more.

Unfortunately, there is no universal truth as to what your purpose in life is. Everyone is unique. Different. We are the product of our upbringing, environment and the cumulative sum of thousands of microdecisions. We need to find meaning for ourselves. Our unique meaning. On this path, we climb alone.

‚ÄúThe Climb‚Äù is created to be raw, unique, beautiful and violently volatile, much like our lives.


Everything is written in javascript and p5js.
It can sometimes take a little while to render on older computers.

metadata.name: Stitched #103
metadata.description:
You are the product of countless tiny decisions taken over the course of your life. Stitched is an attempt to visualize one‚Äôs current self as a product of the myriad forking paths available to us. It is best appreciated in animated format: the latent structure unfolds in time; the past gradually fades away, tinted and obscure. 

Past decisions and missed opportunities leave a trail on the present. Psychology affects what you explore: drive controls how frequent one changes direction; indecisive mints explore many loose ends; balanced mints match complementary colours.

Stitched is adaptive to arbitrary screen resolution and aspect ratio, and best appreciated at high resolution. It initially renders with a large step size in time; pause and unpause to watch it unfold more gradually.

controls:

mouse click or space bar: pause / unpause / reset animation
s: save current frame

Inspired by The Garden of Forking Paths by Borges and stylistically by French and Russian Impressionists, and Autoglyphs by Larva Labs.

metadata.name: Point(); Line(); Plane(); #138
metadata.description:
The title of this piece is a reference to Wassily Kandisky's book "Point and Line to Plane" (1926).

Eight points are placed at random positions, assigned a color and direction, and moved, to become lines. These lines are then translated to form planes.

This idea was already formulated by Aristotle: "a line by its motion produces a surface, and a point by its motion a line".

This simple algorithm creates an interesting variety of compositions, all unique and recognizable.

SVG generated with JavaScript.

The SVG can be exported by pressing "s".

PNG exports can be obtained by pressing "1" (3300√ó1900) or "2" (6600√ó3800).

metadata.name: Bound #311
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten ‚Äì it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself ‚Äì the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold ‚Äì new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we‚Äôve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.
